&#8217;s root or in a subfolder. The Agent is nothing [...]\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Jacques G\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1017:\"<p>The WebsiteDefender service consists of two main components: the Agent which resides in your site to monitor activity, and the Scanning Servers which collect information from the agent to detect and report security threats.</p>\n<p>For WebsiteDefender to work the Agent must be installed in your site&#8217;s root or in a subfolder. The Agent is nothing more than a tiny piece of PHP code that can be described as a security camera that reports your site&#8217;s activity to the Scanning Servers, where information is analyzed and interpreted to identify suspicious activity. The Scanning Servers also receive encrypted copies of your site&#8217;s files for in-depth analysis of any illegal changes which might have been made by a hacker or malware.</p>\n<p>This system of monitoring is guaranteed to avoid false alarms, and performs scans without adding any load on your web server. Additionally, the Agent guarantees that only the site&#8217;s owner can install and run the WebsiteDefender monitoring service.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"http://www.websitedefender.com/faq/how-does-websitedefender-work/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"