('109', '3', '2011-03-24 14:59:00', '2011-03-24 18:59:00', '<p>During my time at <a href=\"http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/index-eng.php\">Health Canada</a> I was added to the HRBSP PeopleSoft Project. Our primary function was to oversea the migration from HR Advantage and the deployment of <a href=\"http://www.oracle.com/us/products/applications/peoplesoft-enterprise/index.html\">PeopleSoft</a>. Within this project my primary function was to create the organizational structure within PeopleSoft that would be the skeleton structure that would accept the migrated data. The two primary components that I worked with were the <a href=\"http://www.canada.gc.ca/depts/major/depind-eng.html\">Department Tree</a> structure as well as the <strong>Location Codes</strong> of the Health Canada and <a href=\"http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/index-eng.php\">Public Health Agency of Canada</a> facilities.</p>', 'PeopleSoft', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'peoplesoft', '', '', '2011-08-29 11:11:11', '2011-08-29 15:11:11', '', '0', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/peoplesoft-2.html', '0', 'post', '', '0'),
('292', '3', '2011-06-29 15:43:05', '2011-06-29 19:43:05', '<p>\r\nThe aviary then transferred my <a href=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/birdcage.html\" title=\"Birdcage\" ><strong>Birdcage</strong></a> into a physical topography at a very large scale. The pavilion found within the aviary was made to look like an extension of the hillside creating a familiar habitat for this merged bird (see <a href=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/birds.html\" title=\"Bird Drawings\" ><strong>Bird Composition</strong></a>). The merged bird can then interact with the other birds in the aviary on the cantilevered section of the pavilion. People who wish to view the birds must travel up the stairs surrounded by waterfalls to reach this cantilevered section.\r\n</p>\r\n[gallery=1]', 'Aviary', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '217-revision-2', '', '', '2011-06-29 15:43:05', '2011-06-29 19:43:05', '', '217', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/217-revision-2.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('312', '3', '2011-07-15 15:34:38', '2011-07-15 19:34:38', '<p>\r\nJust to state outright that I have never read \"Wind-up Bird Chronicle\" and all the following pieces of art were created on the impressions I received from a single passage extracted from this book. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nI just felt like a disclaimer was warranted, if it isn\'t it was still fun to write. Anyway, the below drawings are creations that spawned from reading a short exert of the Wind-up Bird Chronicle. They were all created in a different style, abstract, Escher inspired and clean perspective. Each was a different challenge and I am proud of how all three came out. Even though the perspective is out of place and removed from context (ie. it is a third person perspective derived from a first person narrative). What really came out from this project for me was a better understanding of space, and how it can be used in a two dimensional context, and that it can be even more interesting when these 2D images are transformed into a <strong>three dimensional creation</strong>.\r\n</p>\r\n[gallery=7]', 'Wind-up Bird Chronicle', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '308-revision-3', '', '', '2011-07-15 15:34:38', '2011-07-15 19:34:38', '', '308', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/308-revision-3.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('316', '3', '2011-07-15 15:42:15', '2011-07-15 19:42:15', 'These sketches are a clear representation of my artist ability when I started my studies at <strong>McGill University</strong>. I had to take baby steps, and slowly find my own technique and style. I like these drawings because they are raw and true to myself, they haven\'t been worked and reworked, some of them were even completed in 30 seconds, all of them under 5 minutes. Not enough time to think, just to react. Using such a quick paced method really gets you in the mood to draw and I know that I wouldn\'t of had the confidence to draw full <strong>[intlink id=\"298\" type=\"post\"]portraits[/intlink]</strong> if I hadn\'t started small.\n\n[gallery=5]', 'Sketches from Freehand Drawing 1', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '302-autosave', '', '', '2011-07-15 15:42:15', '2011-07-15 19:42:15', '', '302', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/302-autosave.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('321', '3', '2011-07-29 11:05:25', '2011-07-29 15:05:25', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/cropped-logo.jpg', 'cropped-logo.jpg', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'cropped-logo-jpg', '', '', '2011-07-29 11:05:25', '2011-07-29 15:05:25', '', '0', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/cropped-logo.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'),
('278', '3', '2009-09-18 15:25:44', '2009-09-18 19:25:44', '<p>\r\nWhen I began my adventure in <strong>architecture</strong> I had very little knowledge in the workings of the artistic world. So when the professor detailed the first task of the semester I was both excited and extremely lost. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to draw the movement of a bird. As a recent <strong>physics graduate</strong> I had no idea how to even begin an art assignment. So I began were most who are based in science begin, with a literal representation of a bird. As you can see below I drew my bird in three stop motion frames of his flight. I know the creativity is lacking but this was a personal test of my artistic ability. I put my effort into creating a the best bird I could muster.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThe bird with 3 heads is yet another part of this story. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to take those three drawings and merge them. I chose to superimpose my drawings keeping the body as the central fixed point. The result was a weird and interesting looking creature with 3 heads and 6 wings flying through the air. Looking back I am quite proud of these first drawings and I feel like they were the first stepping stones in my artist journey.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nSome technical info for those who are interested; The 3 birds were drawn with pencil on normal drawing paper and the bird composition was done with ink pen on mylar paper.\r\n</p>\r\n[gallery=3]', 'Bird Drawings', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'birds', '', '', '2011-06-29 15:38:02', '2011-06-29 19:38:02', '', '0', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?p=278', '0', 'post', '', '0'),
('298', '3', '2009-12-11 12:01:35', '2009-12-11 16:01:35', '<p>\r\nFreehand drawing was one of the most liberating experiences of my life. It pushed the perception of what I could do to even greater limits and exposed me to a world I had never taken part in before. As you can see in my gallery my comfort level with different mediums grows exponentially from the <strong>stick figures</strong> I began with to the full mixed media productions at the end. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nIt was fun being able to immerse myself into the world of art 3 hours every friday and I recommend it to anybody thinking of trying something new. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n[gallery=4]\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nThese pieces of art were all done in my freehand drawing class at <strong>McGill University</strong>. Materials include: Pencil, Black ink, charcoal, pastels and gouache were all included somewhere within these works.\r\n</p>', 'Freehand Drawing', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'freehand-drawing', '', '', '2011-07-15 12:10:58', '2011-07-15 16:10:58', '', '0', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?p=298', '0', 'post', '', '0'),
('287', '3', '2011-06-29 15:37:46', '2011-06-29 19:37:46', '<p>\r\nWhen I began my adventure in <strong>architecture</strong> I had very little knowledge in the workings of the artistic world. So when the professor detailed the first task of the semester I was both excited and extremely lost. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to draw the movement of a bird. As a recent <strong>physics graduate</strong> I had no idea how to even begin an art assignment. So I began were most who are based in science begin, with a literal representation of a bird. As you can see below I drew my bird in three stop motion frames of his flight. I know the creativity is lacking but this was a personal test of my artistic ability. I put my effort into creating a the best bird I could muster.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThe bird with 3 heads is yet another part of this story. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to take those three drawings and merge them. I chose to superimpose my drawings keeping the body as the central fixed point. The result was a weird and interesting looking creature with 3 heads and 6 wings flying through the air. Looking back I am quite proud of these first drawings and I feel like they were the first stepping stones in my artist journey.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nSome technical info for those who are interested; The 3 birds were drawn with pencil on normal drawing paper and the bird composition was done with ink pen on mylar paper.\r\n</p>\r\n[gallery=3]', 'Bird Drawings', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '278-revision', '', '', '2011-06-29 15:37:46', '2011-06-29 19:37:46', '', '278', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/278-revision.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
