('297', '3', '2011-06-29 16:24:44', '2011-06-29 20:24:44', 'The birdcage represents the internal structure of a merger between three birds. The use of rib cages represents the idea of a cage found within a bird that anchors it in its physical form. This is the 3rd project in a series of 4 which all began with a drawing of a [intlink id=\"278\" type=\"post\"]<strong>bird</strong>[/intlink]. The birdcage is bent steel wire soldered together to create rib cage like structures.\r\n\r\n[gallery=2]', 'Birdcage', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '258-revision-2', '', '', '2011-06-29 16:24:44', '2011-06-29 20:24:44', '', '258', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/258-revision-2.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('146', '3', '2009-05-21 02:00:14', '2009-05-21 06:00:14', '<h2>On the Nature of Dynamical Instabilities </h2>\r\n<p>\r\nPhysics Department<br>\r\nBishop\'s University\r\n<strong>\r\nThursday, May 21, 2009<br>\r\n1:00 pm\r\n</strong>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThis presentation will explore the theory behind Binary Star Systems (Cataclysmic Variables) and the assumptions under which we are studying these systems. Also it will reveal the results from my calculations obtained using the methods described below.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThrough numerical simulations based on stellar theory and using supercomputers, we are able to theorize about the way binary star systems interact and evolve. For certain initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks are stable. However, given an alternate set of initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks may be highly erratic and unstable. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n[gview file=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/On-the-Nature-of-Dynamical-Instabilities-by-Jacob-Hooey.pdf\"]\r\n</p>\r\n', 'Final Presentation', '', 'trash', 'closed', 'open', '', 'final-presentation', '', '', '2011-08-05 13:47:59', '2011-08-05 17:47:59', '', '71', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?page_id=146', '2', 'page', '', '0'),
('148', '3', '2009-02-13 01:00:27', '2009-02-13 05:00:27', '<h2>Mass Transfer in Binary Star Systems</h2>\r\n<p>\r\nPhysics Department<br>\r\nBishop\'s University\r\n<strong>\r\nFriday, February 13, 2009<br>\r\n12:00 pm\r\n</strong>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThrough numerical simulations based on stellar theory and using supercomputers, we are able to theorize about the way binary star systems interact and evolve. For certain initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks are stable. However, given an alternate set of initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks may be highly erratic and unstable. This presentation will explore the theory behind Binary Star Systems (Cataclysmic Variables) and the assumptions under which we are studying these systems.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n[gview file=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/Mass-Transfer-in-Binary-Star-Systems-by-Jacob-Hooey.pdf\"]\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'MidTerm Presentation', '', 'trash', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'midterm-presentation', '', '', '2011-08-05 13:51:27', '2011-08-05 17:51:27', '', '71', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?page_id=148', '3', 'page', '', '0'),
