('247', '3', '2011-06-23 15:40:04', '2011-06-23 19:40:04', 'On the Nature of Dynamical Instabilities \r\n\r\nPhysics Department\r\nBishop’s University\r\n\r\nThursday, May 21, 2009\r\n1:00 pm\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis presentation will explore the theory behind Binary Star Systems (Cataclysmic Variables) and the assumptions under which we are studying these systems. Also it will reveal the results from my calculations obtained using the methods described below.\r\n\r\n\r\nThrough numerical simulations based on stellar theory and using supercomputers, we are able to theorize about the way binary star systems interact and evolve. For certain initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks are stable. However, given an alternate set of initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks may be highly erratic and unstable. \r\n\r\n\r\n[gview file=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/On-the-Nature-of-Dynamical-Instabilities-by-Jacob-Hooey.pdf\"]\r\n\r\n', '', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', '247', '', '', '2011-06-23 16:08:20', '2011-06-23 20:08:20', '', '71', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?p=247', '8', 'nav_menu_item', '', '0'),
('248', '3', '2011-06-23 15:40:04', '2011-06-23 19:40:04', 'Mass Transfer in Binary Star Systems\r\n\r\nPhysics Department\r\nBishop’s University\r\n\r\nFriday, February 13, 2009\r\n12:00 pm\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThrough numerical simulations based on stellar theory and using supercomputers, we are able to theorize about the way binary star systems interact and evolve. For certain initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks are stable. However, given an alternate set of initial conditions, the resulting evolutionary tracks may be highly erratic and unstable. This presentation will explore the theory behind Binary Star Systems (Cataclysmic Variables) and the assumptions under which we are studying these systems.\r\n\r\n\r\n[gview file=\"http://www.jacobhooey.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/Mass-Transfer-in-Binary-Star-Systems-by-Jacob-Hooey.pdf\"]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', '248', '', '', '2011-06-23 16:08:20', '2011-06-23 20:08:20', '', '71', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/?p=248', '9', 'nav_menu_item', '', '0'),
('286', '3', '2011-06-29 15:26:20', '2011-06-29 19:26:20', '<p>\r\nWhen I began my adventure in <strong>architecture</strong> I had very little knowledge in the workings of the artistic world. So when the professor detailed the first task of the semester I was both excited and extremely lost. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to draw the movement of a bird. As a recent <strong>physics graduate</strong> I had no idea how to even begin an art assignment. So I began were most who are based in science begin, with a literal representation of a bird. As you can see below I drew my bird in three stop motion frames of his flight. I know the creativity is lacking but this was a personal test of my artistic ability. I put my effort into creating a the best bird I could muster.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nThe bird with 3 heads is yet another part of this story. My <strong>studio class</strong> was asked to take those three drawings and merge them. I chose to superimpose my drawings keeping the body as the central fixed point. The result was a weird and interesting looking creature with 3 heads and 6 wings flying through the air. Looking back I am quite proud of these first drawings and I feel like they were the first stepping stones in my artist journey.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nSome technical info for those who are interested; The 3 birds were drawn with pencil on normal drawing paper and the bird composition was done with ink pen on mylar paper.\r\n</p>\r\n[gallery=3]', 'Bird Drawings', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '278-revision-3', '', '', '2011-06-29 15:26:20', '2011-06-29 19:26:20', '', '278', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/278-revision-3.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
('299', '3', '2011-07-15 12:03:45', '2011-07-15 16:03:45', '<p>\nFreehand drawing was one of the most liberating experiences of my life. It pushed the perception of what I could do to even greater limits and exposed me to a world I had never taken part in before. As you can see in my galleries my comfort level with different mediums grows exponentially from the stick figures I began with to the full mixed media productions at the end. \n</p>\n\n<p>\nIt was fun being able to immerse myself into the world of art 3 hours every friday and I recommend it to anybody thinking of trying something new. \n</p>\n<p>\nThese pieces of art were all done in my freehand drawing class at <strong>McGill University</strong>. Materials include: Pencil, Black ink, charcoal, pastels and gouache were all included somewhere within these works.\n</p>\n[gallery=4]', 'Freehand Drawing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '298-revision', '', '', '2011-07-15 12:03:45', '2011-07-15 16:03:45', '', '298', 'http://www.jacobhooey.com/298-revision.html', '0', 'revision', '', '0'),
